gs":["politician"],"sources":[],"prominent_name_reason":"George Edward Murrell (1865-1934) — Member of the Virginia House of Delegates, Bedford County, 1899-1904. Democrat. Chaired the Committee on Retrenchment and the Economy. Son of Mary Ann Hart Murrell (HD0795, great-great-great-great-granddaughter of Thomas Hooker) and John William Murrell of Lynchburg, Virginia. Born July 5, 1865 — weeks before the end of the Confederacy. Source: https://history.house.virginia.gov/members","gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Politician"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"George Edward Murrell","first_name":"George","last_name":"Murrell","middle_name":"Edward","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Born weeks after Appomattox in adjacent Virginia county","body":"George Edward Murrell was born July 5, 1865 in Bedford County Virginia — about three months after Lee's April 9, 1865 surrender at Appomattox in the adjacent Appomattox County. The birth straddled the divide between Virginia's Confederate wartime existence and its Reconstruction-era reorganization. He spent his entire life in the Bedford-Lynchburg area of central Virginia."},{"number":2,"category":"politics","header":"Virginia House of Delegates 1899-1904 Bedford County","body":"George served three two-year terms in the Virginia House of Delegates representing Bedford County from 1899 through 1904 as a Democrat. His committee assignments included Agriculture and Mining, Banks Currency and Commerce, Counties Cities and Towns, Enrolled Bills, Finance, and Retrenchment and the Economy. He chaired the Retrenchment and the Economy committee during his final term — a fiscal-restraint role characteristic of turn-of-the-century Southern Democratic legislators."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Named daughter Mary Hart preserving Hooker family line","body":"George and his wife Mildred Garland had two documented children: Mary Hart Murrell Douville (born 1890) and Mildred Murrell McLeod (born 1903). The elder daughter Mary's middle name Hart deliberately preserved the Hart-Hooker maternal ancestry that connected this Virginia-line branch to the Connecticut Hooker family — the cross-regional naming pattern keeping the family memory alive in the Reconstruction-era Bedford County household."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Bedford Virginia 1865 to Lynchburg Virginia 1934","body":"George Edward Murrell was born July 5, 1865 in Bedford, Virginia and died November 23, 1934 in Lynchburg, Virginia at age sixty-nine. The Bedford-to-Lynchburg life arc remained within the same central Virginia twenty-mile region. His farming-and-politics career combined the two principal occupational paths of his post-war Virginia generation."}],"slug":"george-murrell-1865"},"H00608":{"id":"H00608","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1763,"month":6,"day":24,"city":"Kensington","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1832,"month":3,"day":16,"city":"Hempstead","state":"New York"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00286","mother_research_notes":"Elizabeth Hopkins Hart","mother_id":"X01933"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00535","children_ids":["H01564","H01565","H01566","H01567","H01568","H01569","H01570"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1788,"date_month":10,"date_day":7}],"tags":["yale_connection","episcopal","revolutionary_war","inventor"],"sources":[{"page":"Entry 608","label":"Edward Hooker 1909"},{"url":"https://archive.org/details/biographicalsket04dextuoft/page/342/mode/2up","label":"Dexter — Biographical Sketches Yale Vol 4"}],"gender":"male","narrative_blocks":[{"header":"Yale 1784; ordained by Bishop Seabury; Hempstead rector","detail":"He served as agent for the Connecticut Land Company (1796-1797) surveying lands in Cleveland, Ohio. Among his boarding school students around 1809 was his nephew James Gates Percival (X01936) — son of his sister Elizabeth Hart (H00610) — who later became a noted poet, Connecticut state geologist, and Wisconsin state geologist, writing his final report from memory without notes. The Hofstra University library holds the Hart-Nichols family papers, including correspondence compiled by Seth's granddaughter Mary Amelia Hart (1838-1932). His portrait was painted by Edwin Percival (nephew James Gates's brother) around 1829. (Hart Genealogy 1948; Hofstra Hart-Nichols Family Papers)","body":"Seth Hart graduated Yale in 1784 and was ordained by Bishop Samuel Seabury — deacon in 1791, priest in 1792. He served as rector of St. George's Church in Hempstead, Long Island for 28 years (1800-1829), until paralysis forced his resignation. He died in 1832, 'much beloved and lamented by his former parishioners.'","number":1,"category":"religion"},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"His boarding school launched nephew Percival's poetry","body":"He ran a boarding school at Hempstead where his nephew James Gates Percival was sent in 1807 after their father's death. Despite Percival's resentment of his uncle's 'amiable, cheerful, almost jovial' efforts to draw him out, the Hempstead years were where Percival first wrote poetry."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Officiated Cleveland's first baptism, marriage, and burial","body":"In spring 1797 he went to the Western Reserve of Ohio as General Agent and Chaplain of the surveying party sent by the Connecticut Land Company to develop their settlement at Cleveland. He spent six months in service and officiated at the first baptism, the first marriage, and the first burial occurring in Cleveland."}],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["religion","education"],"notable_blurb":"Yale 1784; rector St. George's Hempstead 28 years","primary_url":"https://www.hofstra.edu/pdf/library/libspc_lisi_oe_hartnichols_selections.pdf","primary_url_label":"Hofstra Hart Nichols Collection"},"institution_affiliations":[],"artworks":["ART024"],"cross_connections":[{"type":"mentor_student","display_label":"His boarding school was where nephew Percival first wrote poetry","related_id":"HD3158","link_text":"James Gates Percival"},{"type":"artifact","related_id":"X01938","display_label":"His portrait painted by his nephew Edwin Percival — a Hooker descendant","link_text":"Edwin Percival"}],"education":[{"institution_id":"INST022","school_name":"Yale College","type":"university","degree":"B.A.","graduation_year":1784,"notable":false,"institution_blurb":"Graduated Yale 1784; became Episcopal rector at Hempstead LI for 28 years."}],"bio":{"title":"Reverend","display_name":"Rev. Seth Hart","first_name":"Seth","last_name":"Hart","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777483052/sethhart1784_armsow.jpg","bio_blurb":"Episcopal rector at Hempstead, Long Island"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002"},{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1784"}],"landmarks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"former_ids":[],"career":[{"role":"Rector","organization":"St. George's Church, Hempstead, Long Island","start_year":1800,"end_year":1829,"notes":"Earlier rector of St. John's, Waterbury and St. Paul's, Wallingford. Yale 1784; ordained by Bishop Seabury."}],"is_placeholder":false,"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM570"},"slug":"seth-hart-1763"},"X00535":{"id":"X00535","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1770,"month":1,"day":1},"death":{"year":1841,"month":11,"day":3,"city":"Hempstead","state":"New York"},"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Hart genealogy","note":"Hart family history; EH 1909 entry 608"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"H00608","children_ids":["H01564","H01565","H01566","H01567","H01568","H01569","H01570"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1788,"date_month":10,"date_day":7}],"gender":"female","parents":{"father_research_notes":"Hon. Benjamin Hall of Cheshire CT"},"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"artworks":["ART025"],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Ruth Hall Hart","first_name":"Ruth","last_name":"Hart","married_names":["Hart"],"maiden_name":"Hall"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM570"},"slug":"ruth-hall-1770"},"H00286":{"id":"H00286","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":5,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1737,"month":1,"day":23,"city":"Kensington","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1811,"month":1,"day":1,"city":"De Ruyter","county":"Madison County","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"I00030","mother_id":"H00101"},"tags":["posthumous_birth"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 286"}],"marriages":[{"children_ids":["H00607","H00608","H00609","H00610","H00611","H00612"],"spouse_id":"X01933","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1759,"date_month":11,"date_day":15,"location_city":"Farmington","location_state":"Connecticut"}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"double_hooker_descent","related_id":"H00534","display_label":"His son Matthew Hart Jr. married Urania Hooker — both.","link_text":"Urania Hooker Hart"},{"type":"double_hooker_descent","related_id":"H00608","display_label":"His son Matthew Hart Jr. married Urania Hooker — both.","link_text":"Rev. Seth Hart"},{"type":"military","display_label":"commanded his Revolutionary militia company","related_id":"H00273","link_text":"Selah Hart"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"bio":{"display_name":"Matthew Hart Jr.","first_name":"Matthew","last_name":"Hart","suffix":"Jr.","married_names":[],"bio_blurb":"Revolutionary War corporal of Kensington"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[{"war":"American Revolutionary War","war_id":"WAR004","rank":"Corporal","rank_start":"Private","rank_end":"Corporal","unit":"Connecticut militia","notes":"Served under Capts. Selah Hart and James Stoddard, Col. Wolcott's regiment."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Born three months after his father died","body":"His father Matthew Hart died on October 30, 1736; he was born January 23, 1737 — a posthumous child. He grew up in Kensington and joined the church there in October 1760 at age twenty-three."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Son's marriage created double Hooker descent","body":"His son Matthew Hart III married Urania Hooker — both Hooker descendants. Their grandchildren carried double descent from Thomas Hooker through different family lines."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Removed his household to New York around 1800","body":"Around the turn of the nineteenth century he sold the Sheldon Moore homestead in Kensington and moved to Madison County, New York — to either Whitestown or De Ruyter. He died there around 1811, more than a decade after the move."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"His grandson became America's foremost 1820s poet","body":"His grandson James Gates Percival (1795-1856) — son of daughter Elizabeth and Dr. James Percival Jr. — became the most recognized American poet of the 1820s and Connecticut's first state geologist. James was born in Kensington before Matthew Hart Jr. departed for New York."},{"number":5,"category":"family","header":"Born after his father had died","body":"Matthew Hart was born in January 1737, weeks after his father died the previous October. He grew up to serve as a Revolutionary corporal and later removed to New York."}],"slug":"matthew-hart-jr-1737"},"X01933":{"id":"X01933","has_descendants_documented":false,"is_placeholder":false,"gender":"female","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1740,"month":11,"day":29,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1817,"month":1,"day":1},"parents":{},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H00286","children_ids":["H00607","H00608","H00609","H00610","H00611","H00612"],"date_year":1759,"date_month":11,"date_day":15,"location_city":"Farmington","location_state":"Connecticut"}],"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"EH 1909; Hart Genealogy 1948"}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Elizabeth Hopkins Hart","first_name":"Elizabeth","last_name":"Hart","maiden_name":"Hopkins","married_names":["Hart"]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"elizabeth-hopkins-1740"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM571","name":"St. John's Episcopal Church Cemetery","city":"Arden","state":"New York","visitable":true,"notes":"St. John's Episcopal Church Cemetery, Arden, Orange County, New York.","hooker_connections":["H01564","X00164"]},"institutionsById":{"INST022":{"id":"INST022","primary_name":"American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions","name":"American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions","alt_names":["ABCFM","American Board"],"type":"missionary_society","founding_year":1810,"location":{"city":"Boston","state":"Massachusetts"},"primary_persons":["X00724"],"hooker_connected_people":["X00724","X02121","X02122","T01213","H00527","I01195"],"person_ids":[],"related_institutions":[],"related_landmarks":[],"tags":["native_american_contact","missionary"],"sources":[{"short":"Wikipedia","note":"Elias Cornelius (clergyman); ABCFM"}],"notes":"First American foreign-mission organization. Tree connections: Rev. Elias Cornelius (agent 1816, secretary 1831-32); Ainsworth and Harriet Ellsworth Blunt, missionaries to the Cherokee at Brainerd, Tennessee; Eliza Talcott, missionary to Japan; Rev. William Banfield Capron, Madura mission; Judge John Hooker, member."}},"crossConnections":[]}